==English==

===Etymology 1===
* '''Either''' from {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|abbreviaten}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|abbreviātus}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|abbreviō||to shorten}}, formed from {{m|la|ad}} + {{m|la|breviō||shorten}}, from {{m|la|brevis||short}} '''or''' {{back-form|abbreviation|lang=en}}<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref>.
* See [[abridge]].

====Pronunciation====
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ə.ˈbriː.vi.eɪt/|lang=en}}
* {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|/əˈbri.vi.eɪt/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-abbreviate.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|abbreviat}}

# {{label|en|obsolete|transitive}} To shorten by omitting parts or details. {{defdate|Attested from around (1350 to 1470) until the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=3}}</ref>
#* {{quote-book|title=Essays|author={{w|Francis Bacon}}|year=1597|passage=It is one thing to '''abbreviate''' by contracting, another by cutting off.}}
# {{label|en|obsolete|intransitive}} To speak or write in a brief manner. {{defdate|Attested from the late 16<sup>th</sup> century until the early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{label|en|transitive}} To make [[short]]er; to [[shorten]]; to [[abridge]]; to shorten by ending sooner than planned. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470).}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{label|en|transitive}} To reduce a word or phrase by means of [[contraction]] or [[omission]] to a shorter recognizable form. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{label|en|transitive|mathematics}} To [[reduce]] to lower terms, as a [[fraction]].

